Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1929, known as Black Thursday, the U.S. stock market experienced a dramatic decline, marking the beginning of a catastrophic financial crisis that contributed to the Great Depression. 

This event followed a period of significant economic optimism during the Roaring Twenties, characterized by rising stock prices and rampant speculation. The crisis began on October 23, when stock prices fell 4.6%, leading to widespread panic among investors. On Black Thursday, an unprecedented 12.9 million shares were traded, far exceeding previous records. This surge overwhelmed stockbrokers, causing delays and inaccuracies in trade reports, which intensified the sense of chaos. In response to the turmoil, police were dispatched to the New York Stock Exchange to maintain order, while Wall Street executives attempted to reassure the public.

Leading up to the crash, many stocks were purchased on margin, meaning investors borrowed money to buy shares, which left them vulnerable to sudden price drops. While some economists had raised alarms about the market's sustainability, many investors remained hopeful, believing prices would continue to rise.

In a bid to stabilize the market, major banks and investment firms intervened by purchasing large blocks of stocks. Initially, this action seemed to quell the panic, as the market closed only slightly down for the day. However, the temporary boost did little to restore confidence. On the following days, known as Black Monday and Black Tuesday, stock prices plummeted further.

The aftermath of Black Thursday triggered a ripple effect across the economy, contributing to decreased manufacturing and rising unemployment. While the crash was a pivotal moment, economists continue to debate whether it was a direct cause of the Great Depression or a symptom of underlying economic weaknesses.

text: I am disappointed that Boeing Machinists and the company could not come to an agreement after yesterday's vote on the latest contract offer. A resolution to the Machinists' strike will restore a critical sector of our district's livelihood, and I hope they can work together to reach an agreement.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1854, in a defining episode of British military history, Lord James Cardigan commanded the Light Brigade cavalry in a disastrous charge against well-fortified Russian artillery during the Battle of Balaklava in the Crimean War. 

Despite the British forces initially gaining the upper hand, Cardigan received an ambiguous order to attack, which led to the ill-fated charge down a valley where the cavalry was met with devastating fire, resulting in around 40% casualties. The order had stemmed from miscommunication among British commanders, and while Cardigan survived, he became a controversial figure, celebrated by some as a national hero while criticized by others for the tragedy.

Name: Diaz-Balart, Mario
text:
I had the great honor of recognizing @mmpizonero, an outstanding resident of Ave Maria, Florida, and a true American patriot. He selflessly took a bullet to save a mother and her four children, prioritizing their safety over his own.

Thanks to the bravery of the Collier County Sheriff’s Office and the Immokalee Fire Control District, who acted quickly to get him to the hospital, Manuel narrowly escaped with his life.

Our community is fortunate to have heroes like Manuel and dedicated first responders. They all inspire hope for the future of America and demonstrate that humanity and solidarity still exist.

For these reasons, I had the privilege of presenting Manuel with a Congressional Record for his heroism and also presenting a certificate of Congressional Recognition to all the first responders who saved Manuel’s life and brought to justice the suspect who threatened to kill a mother and her four children.

Name: Diaz-Balart, Mario
text:
Tuve el gran honor de expresar mi reconocimiento a Manuel Milanés Pizonero, un destacado residente de Ave Maria, Florida, y un verdadero patriota americano. Manuel recibió un disparo por salvar a una madre y sus cuatro hijos, priorizando su bienestar por encima del suyo.
 
Gracias a la valentía demostrada por los miembros de la Oficina del Sheriff del Condado de Collier y el Distrito de Control de Incendios de Immokalee, que actuaron rápidamente para llevarlo al hospital y Manuel logro evadir el riesgo de perder la vida.
 
Nuestra comunidad tiene la suerte de contar con héroes como Manuel y el personal de respuesta a emergencias. Todos ellos inspiran esperanza para el futuro de Estados Unidos y demuestran que existe humanidad y solidaridad.
 
Por estas razones, tuve el privilegio de presentar a Manuel con un Registro del Congreso por su heroísmo y también de presentar un Certificado de Reconocimiento del Congreso al personal de respuesta a emergencias que salvaron la vida de Manuel y en llevar ante la justicia al sospechoso que amenazó matar a una madre y sus cuatro hijos.

Dr. Mary Stephenson, born in Red Oak and now residing in Roanoke Rapids, has served K-12 schools in Bertie and Northampton counties as a teacher, mentor, assistant principal, principal, director of elementary education, and director of federal programs. She is also a part-time faculty member in the Department of Education at Elizabeth City State University and serves as the liaison for the 2+2 Partnership Program between Elizabeth City State University and Halifax Community College.

Her dedication to our community is evident through her numerous service activities, including donation drives, tutoring, senior citizen engagement, and youth symposiums. Dr. Stephenson remains active with the Halifax-Northampton Retired School Personnel and the Mu Theta Chapter of Sigma Gamma Rho Sorority, Inc.

With 50 years of experience in education and ongoing community involvement, Dr. Stephenson shows no signs of slowing down as she continues to make a positive impact on eastern North Carolina.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Each week, we share the remarkable stories of Hometown Heroes from across our district. Today, we shine a spotlight on an extraordinary young girl whose strength and compassion exemplify what it truly means to be a hero. Meet this week’s Hometown Hero—ten-year-old Francesca "Frankie" Wilson of Chalfont.
 
At just five years old, after her father Dan was diagnosed with lung cancer, Frankie went to school, grabbed the microphone at lunch, and rallied her peers to join her in prayer. But that was only the beginning of her journey as an advocate. Frankie became a driving force behind Links for Lungs, the nonprofit her family launched to raise funds for lung cancer research. Year after year, Frankie has been front and center, hosting lemonade stands and working at the family’s golf outings to ensure no family facing lung cancer feels alone. With every action she has taken, she shows that even the youngest among us can be powerful agents of change.
 
Then, in a heartbreaking twist, this February, Frankie faced a battle of her own—her own cancer diagnosis. But where others might falter, Frankie drew from her strength and faith, meeting the challenge with the same resolve she has shown for years. 
 
Even as she endures months of chemotherapy, radiation, and the possibility of surgery, Frankie’s advocacy hasn’t slowed. She speaks openly about her diagnosis with friends, offering them a space to ask questions. In the hospital, she encourages other children—comforting them with kind words about feeding tubes, hair loss, and nutrition. Her mother, Brittany, put it best: “She embraces everything with her spunky spirit.”
 
Frankie Wilson teaches us a profound lesson: no matter the size of the struggle, we always have the choice to meet it with courage, love, and grace. Her resilience shows us that even in life's most difficult moments, we can still choose hope, find purpose, and make an impact on the world around us.
 
Please join me in celebrating and praying for this extraordinary young lady and the entire Wilson family. Frankie, your courage and spirit inspire us all. Your community stands with you, cheering you on every step of the way. God bless you, Frankie—you are a true Hometown Hero.

Gateway is essential to our health system, and this clinic will provide Laredo residents with the quality care they need. I want to thank Elmo Lopez, Lauro Garcia, City Councilwoman Alyssa Cigarroa, Mayor Dr. Victor Trevino, and the entire Gateway staff for their dedication.

I also secured $6,005,040 from the Health Resources and Services Administration to support all Gateway clinics.

I remain committed to advocating for accessible health care in our communities.

Did you know that prescription drugs are often thrown in the trash, where they can be retrieved, abused, or illegally sold? It's important to note that you should NOT throw away or flush expired or unneeded prescription drugs down the drain.

Official prescription drug collection sites are a great way to safely dispose of your unneeded or leftover prescriptions.

Tomorrow, October 26th, be sure to swing by a participating location to drop off any prescription drugs you no longer need.

The Drug Enforcement Administration (DEA) has a comprehensive list of participating locations across the country, including throughout Northern Ohio.

Click on the link below to find your nearest location.

Our response to this breach must not only mitigate the immediate threat but serve as a launching point for long-term, strategic solutions to safeguard our networks. Protecting our infrastructure is about more than just technology—it’s about ensuring the security, prosperity, and safety of every American.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1881, the Earp brothers confronted the Clanton-McLaury gang in the most famous Wild West shootout at the O.K. Corral in Tombstone, Arizona. 

Tombstone had rapidly developed into a wealthy mining town after silver was discovered nearby in 1877. Wyatt Earp, a former police officer, and his brothers, Morgan and Virgil (the town marshal), embodied law enforcement but were also seen as ruthless. The Clantons and McLaurys were cowboys involved in cattle rustling and criminal activities. Tensions between these groups escalated, leading to the deadly confrontation at the O.K. Corral.

The day prior, Ike Clanton and Tom McLaury arrived in Tombstone for supplies and quickly clashed with the Earp brothers and Doc Holliday. The following afternoon, Ike's brother Billy, along with Frank McLaury and Billy Claiborne, joined them. At a local saloon, they learned from Holliday that their brothers had been pistol-whipped by the Earps, prompting Frank and Billy to seek revenge.

By 3 p.m., the Earps and Holliday encountered the Clanton-McLaury gang in a vacant lot near the O.K. Corral. The ensuing gunfight lasted about 30 seconds, with around 30 shots fired. Most accounts suggest that Virgil Earp fired the first shot, hitting Billy Clanton, while Doc Holliday shot Tom McLaury. Frank McLaury and Billy Clanton also returned fire but were both fatally wounded. Ike Clanton and Claiborne fled the scene.

Sheriff John Behan charged the Earps and Holliday with murder, but a month later, a judge found them not guilty, stating they were justified in their actions. The shootout has since been depicted in numerous films, including 𝐹𝑟𝑜𝑛𝑡𝑖𝑒𝑟 𝑀𝑎𝑟𝑠ℎ𝑎𝑙 and 𝑇𝑜𝑚𝑏𝑠𝑡𝑜𝑛𝑒.

Name: Van Duyne, Beth
text:
Vernon “Vern” Mitchell, 103 years old, of Fort Worth, enlisted in the U.S. Army at the age of 19. He was assigned to the 2nd Infantry Division where he was deployed and wounded in the Battle of Normandy by a German artillery shell that killed two of his squad members. Vern is a recipient of France's Legion of Honor, The Purple Heart, Bronze Star, World War II Victory Medal, and many more. In his own words, “The United States is a shining light on a hill for the world to see. Our country is worth fighting for.”

My bipartisan bills have passed the House to cut wasteful spending, keep our woods working, and help more small businesses access federal contracting opportunities.

I’ve also led efforts to take on our national debt by introducing bipartisan legislation to create a more effective budget process and a Constitutional amendment to require Congress to balance our budget.

To avoid passing on more debt to our children, I’ll keep working with my bipartisan colleagues on commonsense efforts to cut government excesses, reduce our deficit, and be responsible stewards of taxpayer dollars.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1919, Congress passed the Volstead Act, overriding President Wilson's veto, to enforce the 18th Amendment, which established Prohibition. 

The push for alcohol prohibition began in the early 19th century with temperance societies, gaining momentum by the late 19th century as these groups became politically influential. The 18th Amendment was ratified in January 1919, making it illegal to manufacture, sell, or transport intoxicating liquors.

The Volstead Act, enacted later that year, aimed to enforce these laws, including forming a special Treasury unit. However, it struggled to curb the illegal alcohol trade, leading to a rise in organized crime. Figures like Al Capone became notorious during this time, illustrating how organized crime thrived in response to the ban on alcohol.

The era also saw the rise of speakeasies—illegal bars that became popular social hubs. Ultimately, Prohibition was repealed in 1933 by the 21st Amendment.

Name: Cuellar, Henry
text:
Today, I announced $2,690,608 in federal funding to enhance mental health support for the San Antonio Independent School District (SAISD). 

This funding, from the Department of Education’s Mental Health Service Professional Demonstration Grant, will support the Con Cariño initiative, improving the internship-to-employment pipeline for licensed Master Social Workers.

The grant will place four social work interns and two school psychology interns in the district, addressing the need for more licensed mental health professionals. Local graduate students will gain hands-on experience while receiving compensation and support for licensing exam costs, helping to retain staff who understand community needs.

I have previously secured funding for SAISD, including resources for school lunch reimbursements. I will continue to advocate for federal support to expand mental health services for our students.

Name: Perez, Marie Gluesenkamp
text:
I am incredibly thankful to the local first responders who quickly arrived on scene, put out the fire, and salvaged the ballots they could.

There is absolutely zero place in our democracy for political violence or interference against our fellow citizens, election workers, or voting infrastructure.

I hope the perpetrator of this reprehensible act is quickly apprehended – and local and federal law enforcement have my full support in working to keep our democratic process safe and secure.

Our right to vote needs to be protected under all circumstances. We can’t yield to intimidation, and we must continue to stand up against unpatriotic acts such as this one.

Your vote matters, so I encourage everyone who dropped off a ballot this weekend at the Fisher’s Landing Transit Center to get in touch with the Clark County Elections Office and request a replacement.

I am requesting an overnight law enforcement presence be posted at all ballot drop boxes in Clark County through Election Day. Southwest Washington cannot risk a single vote being lost to arson and political violence. 

I’ll continue to closely monitor this situation and share resources and updates with constituents who may have been affected.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1998, nearly four decades after becoming the first American to orbit the Earth, Senator John Glenn launched into space again aboard the space shuttle Discovery at age 77, making him the oldest person to travel in space. 

Glenn was a decorated U.S. Marine Corps lieutenant colonel and one of NASA's first astronauts selected in 1959. He had a distinguished military career, flying nearly 150 combat missions and making the first nonstop supersonic flight across the U.S. in 1957.

Following Yuri Gagarin's historic flight in 1961, Glenn's Friendship 7 mission made him a national hero as it orbited the Earth three times. He was celebrated with a visit from President Kennedy and a ticker-tape parade.

After his historic flight, Glenn was largely sidelined by NASA due to concerns for his safety. He turned to politics, running for the U.S. Senate from Ohio, but withdrew due to an injury. He eventually won a Senate seat and was re-elected three times, serving until his retirement in 1999.

He returned to space in 1998, drawing significant media attention. During the nine-day mission, he participated in a NASA study on aging. Glenn passed away in 2016 at the age of 95.

Name: Cuellar, Henry
text:
I announced $270 million in federal funding for the VIA Metropolitan Transit’s Advanced Rapid Transit Green Line project and nearly $1.7 million for the Brooks Development Authority.

This funding will significantly improve transportation for San Antonio residents, particularly in underserved areas, enhancing access to education and jobs. I extend my gratitude to VIA leadership, the Brooks Development Board, and our local representatives for their partnership and support. This achievement reflects a collaborative effort among all of us involved.

The Green Line will include dedicated lanes, off-board fare collection, and transit-priority traffic signals to reduce travel times. Of the total funding, $158 million comes from the FY23 Appropriations Bill, with an additional $110 million earmarked for the 2025 budget.

Additionally, the Brooks Development funding will support the installation of 24 publicly accessible EV charging stations at Brooks City Base, improving accessibility for local residents.

I remain committed to advocating for essential infrastructure funding that enhances our communities’ quality of life.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text: Breaking the cycle of recidivism is one of the most critical steps we can take in building safer, stronger communities. Too often, people leave incarceration only to face the same struggles—untreated mental health issues, inadequate care, and missing support. The Outmate Program is a proactive solution that gives individuals the tools to rebuild their lives, stay on course, and reintegrate successfully. When we help people succeed after incarceration, we strengthen our neighborhoods, reduce pressure on the justice system, and create lasting change. I’m proud to have secured funding for this transformative initiative.

Name: Murkowski, Lisa
text:
Yesterday, I was scheduled to fly to Kotzebue to meet with the local leadership, first responders, and the National Guard about the recent flooding. Unfortunately, another inbound storm meant we had to cancel the trip.

https://t.co/0U2dJHCVep

Name: Murkowski, Lisa
text: It’s been heartbreaking seeing pictures of flooded homes with foundation cracks, interior water damage, and soaked insulation as the temperature continue to drop – all while residents already face $9 a gallon for diesel fuel for heating.

Name: Murkowski, Lisa
text: Families have lost their firewood reserves, and saltwater from the flooding has severely damaged engines in snowmachines and four-wheelers, which locals depend on for hunting and replenishing their woodpiles. Kotzebue is really hurting right now.

Name: Murkowski, Lisa
text: But watching neighbors in the community, National Guard members, and volunteers from the @forestservice come together to help with the recovery efforts has been truly uplifting.

Name: Murkowski, Lisa
text:
@ANTHCtoday and the Healthy Alaska Natives Foundation have partnered with the Native Village of Kotzebue to manage a rapid response fund that will help the village respond to the damage from the flood.

https://t.co/0U2dJHDt3X

Name: Murkowski, Lisa
text: I’m incredibly proud of the joint effort from so many different corners of the state to help Kotzebue. In Alaska, we help our neighbors weather the storm.

Name: Castro, Joaquin
text:
Everyone in San Antonio should be able to count on secure, reliable mail delivery.

USPS delivers everything from medication to paychecks – but as Postmaster General Louis DeJoy has pushed for major cost cuts over the last four years, postal service has started to falter. 🧵

Name: Castro, Joaquin
text:
Last year, USPS ended a long-standing policy of providing water bottles to letter carriers who deliver mail in the hot summer heat. 

@RepCasar and I pushed back, but it was a troubling sign of what would come.

Name: Castro, Joaquin
text:
At the same time, USPS has abandoned its responsibility to maintain neighborhood cluster boxes – the centralized facilities that make delivery easier and cheaper for the post office.

https://t.co/rN7ehGN9Xc

Name: Castro, Joaquin
text: Today, USPS is asking neighborhood associations to pay tens of thousands of dollars to repair damaged or vandalized mailboxes – even in situations where USPS had previously maintained the boxes for decades.

Name: Castro, Joaquin
text:
Over the summer, USPS announced a new plan to consolidate South Texas mail processing in San Antonio – adding new strain to our local mail centers and potentially delaying delivery for thousands of households.

We fought back – and they backed down.

https://t.co/BewArqBbK2

Name: Castro, Joaquin
text: Last week, my office visited the Kingwood Heights, Parkwood, Northwest Crossing, and Westover Elms neighborhoods to meet with people who have struggled to get help from the USPS after their cluster boxes were vandalized or damaged. https://t.co/aCT6clrd1E

Name: Castro, Joaquin
text:
We also heard from neighbors who had to wait in long lines for mail because their cluster boxes were out of service.

People deserve to have faith in the postal system. I'm pushing USPS to fix these issues — and I won't stop until neighborhoods get the service they need.
